usage_msg = """\
NAME
    safewrite - Write a file only if unchanged since last read (advisory lock + compare-and-swap)

SYNOPSIS
    safewrite TARGET (--from SOURCE | --stdin) [--expect-sha256 HASH] [--note TEXT]
        [--lock-root DIR] [--ttl SECS] [--wait SECS] [--owner LABEL] [--allow-empty-write]
        [--backup-to PATH] [--max-shrink-pct PCT] [--sentinel-regex RE]

DESCRIPTION
    Writes new content to TARGET only if the file's current sha256 matches
    --expect-sha256, using an advisory mkdir lock to serialize concurrent writers
    and a heartbeat thread to detect and recover from crashed agents.

    Caller protocol:
      1. Read TARGET and record its sha256 (shasum -a 256 TARGET | awk '{print $1}')
      2. Prepare new content
      3. Invoke safewrite with --expect-sha256 set to the hash from step 1
      If the file changed between steps 1 and 3, the write is aborted (exit 3).

    Writes in-place (truncate + rewrite), preserving the inode. File watchers and
    open file descriptors continue to see the file at the same inode.

    Lock files live under --lock-root (default: /tmp/safewrite.locks/).
    All cooperating agents must use the same --lock-root to rendezvous.
    A lock held by a crashed writer (heartbeat older than --ttl seconds) is
    automatically broken and the stale owner and note are logged to stderr.

    fhold decides whether writes stay in review mode or switch to permit
    mode; safewrite is the permit-mode writer that makes concurrent,
    unreviewed writes safe via CAS locking.

ARGUMENTS
    TARGET                File to write (created if it does not exist)

OPTIONS
    --from SOURCE         Read new content from SOURCE. Preferred over --stdin for
                          existing files: content can be verified before write and
                          cannot be zeroed by pipe failure.
    --stdin               Read new content from stdin.
    --expect-sha256 HASH  SHA-256 of TARGET as caller last read it; aborts with exit 3
                          if the file has since changed. Omit to skip CAS check.
                          If TARGET does not yet exist, its effective sha256 is that of
                          the empty string (e3b0c44298fc...); omit this flag to create
                          unconditionally.
    --note TEXT           Free-form label stored in lock metadata: agent name, task ID,
                          prompt summary, etc. Shown in stderr when a stale lock breaks.
    --lock-root DIR       Directory for lock entries (default: /tmp/safewrite.locks)
                          Must be shared by all cooperating writers.
    --ttl SECS            Stale lock TTL in seconds (default: 120)
    --wait SECS           Max seconds to wait for lock acquisition (default: 30)
    --owner LABEL         Owner label in lock metadata (default: $USER)
    --allow-empty-write   Allow 0-byte writes to non-empty TARGET (default: blocked).
                          Without this flag, any 0-byte input from --from/--stdin aborts
                          when TARGET exists and is non-empty (exit 1).
    --backup-to PATH      Write a pre-write backup of TARGET content.
                          If PATH is a directory (existing, or ending with '/'), backup
                          file name is TARGET basename with a date-timestamp variant.
                          If PATH is a filename, writes exactly to PATH.
    --max-shrink-pct PCT  Abort if output shrinks by more than PCT versus current TARGET.
    --sentinel-regex RE   Require regex RE to match output before write.

    -H, --raw-help        Show this raw usage text and exit
    -h, --help            Show colorized usage and exit

EXIT CODES
    0  success
    1  usage error (bad arguments)
    2  lock acquisition timeout
    3  CAS mismatch — file changed since --expect-sha256 was recorded
    4  post-write verification failure

EXAMPLE
    HASH=$(shasum -a 256 config.json | awk '{print $1}')
    safewrite config.json \\
        --from new_config.json --expect-sha256 "$HASH" \\
        --note "agent=claude, task=abc123"
"""

# usage_msg is intentionally placed at the very top for human readers and future agents.
# usage_msg formatting and content ALWAYS trumps show_usage(). If you change usage_msg,
# you MUST update show_usage() to match it EXACTLY, including newlines and spacing.
# Agents must not update usage_msg without explicit instructions to do so.
# When they aren't in sync, agents must update show_usage()'s underlying
